3.	(Demolition and Construction Management & Logistics Plan): Prior to the commencement of  development a Demolition & Construction Management and Logistics Plan shall be submitted to and            approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.  The Plan shall include details of:

a)        Demolition Plans;
b)       The location of notice board/s on the site to include details of the site manager, including contact details (phone, facsimile, email, postal address); 
c)	A strategy for the parking of vehicles of site operatives and visitors; 
d)	A strategy for the loading and unloading of plant and materials; 
e)	A strategy for the storage of plant and materials used in constructing the development; 
f)	Details of the erection and maintenance of security hoarding including decorative displays and facilities for public viewing, where appropriate; 
g)	Details of any means of protection of services such as pipes and water mains within the road; 
h)	Measures to be adopted to maintain the site in a tidy condition in terms of disposal/storage of rubbish, storage and unloading of building materials and similar construction activities; 
i)	Measures to be adopted to ensure that pedestrian access past the site on the public footpaths is safe and not obstructed during construction works; 
j)	Location of workers' conveniences (e.g. toilets, showers); 
k)	Reasonable measures to be adopted, such as a restriction on the size of construction vehicles and machinery accessing the site, to minimise any potential damage occurring to adjacent                       streets throughout the construction period; 
l)	Location of vehicle and construction machinery access during the period of site works including identification of any works necessary to the public highway necessary to provide a means of                       access during the construction and/or operation of the development; 
m)	Numbers and timing of truck movements throughout the day and the proposed routes broken down by size of trucks; 
n)	Vehicle holding areas; 
o)	Construction traffic routes; 
p)	Procedures including wheel washing for controlling sediment runoff, dust and the removal of soil, debris and demolition and construction materials from public roads or places; 
q)	Communication  with other high-risk construction sites within 500 m radius of the site; and 
r)	A Demolition and Construction Site Waste Management Plan (WMP) which includes details of managing construction waste having regard to the site waste hierarchy (prevention, reuse, recycling, recovery, safe disposal), preferred options for storage and management  (placed in segregated skips to be provided, target monitoring, any deviations from waste procedures to be documented and remedial action carried out by the contracts manager

The development hereby permitted shall only be carried out in accordance with the approved details.

Reason: In order to comply with Local Plan Policy LP22 and London Plan policies SI 7 & T7 to ensure that the construction of the development is undertaken in a manner which minimises its' effect on the local environment. 

The objectives and purposes of this condition are such that it is required to be complied with before commencement. As such, those objectives and purposes would not be met if expressed other than as a pre-commencement condition.


4.	(Construction Environmental Management Plan): Prior to the commencement of development hereby approved, a Construction Environmental Management Plan (CEMP) shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. This shall cover:

The CEMP shall include details of the following:
a)	Hours of work (if altered from not being outside 08:00 to 18:00 hours Mondays to Fridays, 08.00 to 13.00 hours Saturdays and no works on Sundays or Public Holidays);
b)	Details of any noise screening measures;
c)	Proposals for monitoring noise and procedures to be put in place where agreed noise levels are exceeded; and
d)	Where works are likely to lead to vibration impacts on surrounding residential properties, proposals for monitoring vibration and procedures/mitigation to be put in place if agreed vibration levels are exceeded. Vibration over 1mm/s measured as a peak particle velocity would constitute unreasonable vibration.

In particular the applicant shall:

e)	Submit for approval a Construction Dust Management Plan, including details of mitigation measures for dust and emissions during demolition and/or construction along with a monitoring regime for the same (inc Asbestos control); Reference shall be made to the Mayor of London's Control of Dust and Emissions from Construction and Demolition Best Practice Guidance.
f)	Submit a Dust Monitoring Programme for approval;
g)	Submit a Detailed Demolition Noise Assessment based on, but not limited to, the demolition timetable, technical specification of plant being used and include mitigation required;
h)	Equipment and plant used on site shall comply with the requirements for 'Non-Road Mobile Machinery' (NRMM);
i)	Shall clarify the type of piling proposed within the operations chapter of the CEMP;
j)	Include a copy of the Site Waste Management Plan; and
k)	Shall submit details on storage and stockpiling of wastes at the site.

Reason: To ensure considerate construction and to protect the amenities of the nearby residents and/or businesses from excessive noise and dust and to comply with Local Plan Policies LP22, LP24 and LP26, and London Plan policies GG3, SI 1, D14 and the GLA non-road mobile machinery (NRMM) low emission zone (LEZ). 

The objectives and purposes of this condition are such that it is required to be complied with before commencement of development. As such, those objectives and purposes would not be met if the condition were to be expressed other than as a pre-commencement condition.


5.	(Land contamination): 

1. The following details are required prior to commencement of development. 

A sufficient ground gas and vapour monitoring programme is undertaken and submitted to the LPA. The full methodology and detailed results of the investigation shall be provided. A ground gas / vapour risk assessment and human health risk assessment for the end-users of the site shall be provided.

Where the ground gases / vapours are found to pose an unacceptable risk for future development, no construction works shall take place until a detailed remediation scheme has been submitted to, and approved by, the Local Planning Authority. A verification plan shall be included in the scheme to ensure remediation objectives and criteria will be met. 

The remediation works shall be undertaken in accordance with the approved details. The scheme once completed must ensure that the site will not qualify as 'Contaminated Land' under Part 2A of the Environmental Protection Act 1990 in relation to its intended use. 

2. Prior to occupation of the development. 

A verification plan demonstrating completion of works set out in the approved remediation strategy and the effectiveness of the remediation, shall be submitted to, and approved, in writing by the Local Planning Authority. 

Reason: In the interests of future health of occupiers of the development, in accordance with Policy LP24.


6.	(Employment, Skills and Training): Prior to the commencement of development, a detailed Employment, Skills and Training strategy prepared in line with Redbridge Planning Obligation SPD shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The strategy shall include:

a)	Local People Employment Requirement including total number of construction phase job with a minimum of 12 weeks employment, and reasonable endeavours to use 20% of overall operational jobs for Redbridge Residents.
b)	Apprenticeship including total number of construction apprentice and support fee provided before and throughout the construction phase of the development.
c)	Training and Skills and Financial Contributions including Construction phase training and job brokerage provided prior to the construction phase of the development and End-use phase training and job brokerage provided throughout the build project.

The development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved strategy.

Reason: to maximise opportunities for residents to enter into apprenticeships and training programmes and provide them with new skills to help them in the job market in accordance with LP16 and LP 41.


7.	(Carbon off-setting fund contribution): Prior to commencement of the development a strategy detailing phased payment of 50% of carbon off-set fund contribution prior to substantial implementation and 50% prior to occupation following final calculation in line with GLA calculator upon completion of the development and demonstrated in a revised Energy Statement shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.

Reason: In order to minimise greenhouse gas emission through ring-fencing the contribution towards implementation of project that deliver carbon reduction and to comply with London Plan Policy SI2 and Local Plan Policy LP20. 


8.	(Upgrade pedestrian crossing on Perth Road): Prior to the commencement of development, a detailed strategy to upgrade the existing informal pedestrian crossing on Perth Road (to the north of the car park entrance) to provide a raised zebra crossing shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.

The development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved strategy.

Reason: In order to facilitate the safe and convenient movement of pedestrians to and from the site and to encourage sustainable modes of travel in accordance with Local Plan Policy LP22 and London Plan Policy T2.


9.	(Biodiversity Gain Plan): Development may not be begun unless -

(a) a biodiversity gain plan has been submitted to the planning authority; and
(b) the planning authority has approved the plan.

Reason: As required by Schedule 7A to the Town and Country Planning Act 1990


10.	(Biodiversity Monitoring): Prior to the commencement of the development, a detailed Biodiversity Net Gain reporting and monitoring strategy shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. 

Reason: As required by Schedule 7A to the Town and Country Planning Act 1990


ABOVE GROUND WORKS CONDITIONS 

11.	(SuDS- Drainage Details):  Prior to commencement of groundworks (excluding site investigations and demolition), the applicant must submit a final detailed drainage design including drawings and supporting calculations to the Lead Local Flood Authority for review and approval, aligned with the Flood Risk Assessment (30th May 2024) and associated drawings. A detailed management plan confirming routine maintenance tasks for all drainage components must also be submitted to demonstrate how the drainage system is to be maintained for the lifetime of the development. 

Reason: To prevent the risk of flooding to and from the site in accordance with relevant policy requirements including but not limited to London Plan Policy SI 13, its associated Sustainable Design and Construction SPG, the Non-Statutory Technical Standards for Sustainable Drainage Systems and Redbridge Council's Local Plan Policy LP 21. 


12.	(SuDS - Discharge Point Connection): Prior to the connection to the Thames Water Sewer System, confirmation and evidence that consent for the proposed discharge point connection has been obtained from Thames Water shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. 

Reason: To comply with the London Plan Policy SI 13.


13.	('Be Seen' Energy Monitoring): Prior to the above ground works, a detailed strategy for actual operational energy performance monitoring, verification and reporting to the GLA via the GLA's Energy Monitoring Portal in line with 'Be Seen' energy monitoring guidance, September 2021 shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.

The reporting shall be carried out in accordance with the approved strategy.

Reason: To ensure that the actual energy and carbon performance of buildings is aligned with the estimated energy and contribute in achieving a zero-carbon in accordance with London Plan Policy SI2. 


14.	(Facing Materials): Notwithstanding the details submitted with the proposal hereby approved, prior to the above ground works, samples / plans (as appropriate) of all facing materials, shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The details shall also include:

a)	Brickwork;
b)	Concrete Panel;
c)	Windows and doors (including reveals and frames);
d)	Canopies;
e)	External guttering;
f)	Noticeboards;
g)	Signage (not otherwise requiring Advertisement Consent);
h)	Plant enclosures;
i)	Stairs;
j)	Gates;
k)	Boundary wall and fence;

The development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details.

Reason: To ensure that the external appearance of the building is satisfactory in accordance with the requirements of policy LP26 of the Council's Local Plan.


15.	(Electric vehicle charging Points (EVCP):  Prior to the first occupation/use of the development, details of electric vehicle charging point locations and technical specifications associated with the two proposed wheelchair parking spaces shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The development shall be implemented in accordance with the approved details and retained as such thereafter for the lifetime of the development unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority. 

The EVCP infrastructure as approved shall be operational prior to the first occupation/use of the development.

Reason: In the interest of effective provision of safe and well-designed parking 	facilities in accordance with Local Plan Policy LP23 and Policy T6 of the London Plan.


16.	(External lighting): Prior to the above ground works, an external lighting scheme shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The scheme shall take into account all of the lighting needs associated with the development during operational hours and shall be the minimum required to perform the relevant lighting task. It shall be specifically designed to minimise the risk of light spillage beyond the development site boundary and into the sky and to avoid dazzle or distract drivers on nearby roads. 

The scheme shall include: 

(a)	A statement setting out and justifying why the lighting scheme is required; 

(b)	A report, prepared by a professional lighting engineer, setting out the technical details of the luminaires and columns, including their location, type, shape, dimensions and, expected luminance output and specifically explaining what design attributes have been chosen to minimise light pollution; 

(c)	A plan illustrating illuminance levels across the development site and at the boundary of the site. The level of illuminance should be appropriate to the character of the surrounding area as a whole. Four environmental zones are internationally recognised, and the design will require to show that control of overspill light is limited to the level required by the particular environmental setting;

(d)	A plan illustrating illuminance levels beyond the boundary of the site, together with the downward light output ratio of the lights; 

(e)	A statement which demonstrates how the lighting scheme will be viewed against the wider landscape and, where appropriate, the potential role of landscaping in minimizing the day and night-time visual impact of the installation; 

(f)	An operational statement, the purpose of which is to ensure that the developer and the lighting designer have considered operational regimes that can provide energy savings; and 

(g)	Details of the proposed hours of operation. (Unless explicitly agreed in writing, all external lighting luminaries shall be turned off during daylight hours and when not actively required. 

(h)	The detailed design including positioning, duration, type of light source etc of the external lighting to demonstrate it will minimise the impact on wildlife.

Once approved in writing, the lighting scheme shall be implemented prior to the occupation/use of the development and thereafter be operated in accordance with the approved details for the lifetime of the development.

Reason: To protect the amenity of the locality, in terms of light pollution especially for people living and/or working nearby, in accordance with Policies LP24 and LP26 of the Local Plan.


PRIOR TO OCCUPATION CONDITIONS

17.	(SuDS - Evidence of SuDS Scheme): No building hereby permitted shall be occupied until evidence (photographs and installation contracts) is submitted to demonstrate that the sustainable drainage scheme for the site has been completed in accordance with the submitted details. The sustainable drainage scheme shall be managed and maintained thereafter in accordance with the agreed management and maintenance plan for all of the proposed drainage components. The name of the maintenance owner of the SuDS should be provided. 

Reason: To comply with the Non-Statutory Technical Standards for Sustainable Drainage Systems, the National Planning Policy Framework (Paragraph 103), the London Plan (Policies SI 12 and SI 13) along with associated guidance to these policies and Redbridge Council's Local Plan Policy LP 21.


18.	(Secure by Design): Each building, or part of a building, shall obtain a 'Secured By Design' Accreditation prior to first occupation of each building or part of a building, or use. The development shall only be carried out in accordance with the approved details and maintained thereafter. 

Reason: To ensure that Secured by Design principles are implemented into the development as far as reasonable and in accordance with Policy LP26 of the Local Plan and Policy D11 of the London Plan.


19.	(Cycle Parking Detail): Notwithstanding any details of cycle parking shown in approved plans, prior to the first occupation/use of the development, details of all cycle parking for the visitors and staff, shall be submitted to approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The cycle parking details shall demonstrate: 

a)	Cycle parking and proposed areas are in line with the London Cycling Design Standards. 
b)	a minimum of one long stay cycle space for the staff be suitable for long-stay parking in terms of location, security and protection from the elements and inclement weather. 
c)	Accessible facilities for disabled cyclists.

	The cycle parking thereby approved shall be installed as per the approved details 	and retained, not used for any other purpose and be maintained in good working 	order.  

Reason: To ensure appropriate support facilities for cyclists are provided in the 	scheme and to comply with policy T5 of the London Plan. 


20.	(PV Array): Notwithstanding the details under condition 2 of this permission, and prior to the first occupation/use of the development details shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority to demonstrate how the proposed  PV array  will be maximised to assist output and electricity generation to the development.  The details shall include the exact location of the PV array and provide confirmation the estimated area, output and electricity generation. 

The approved details shall be installed and be operational before first occupation of the relevant Phase and retained in perpetuity. 

Reason: In order to ensure the development complies with the terms of the application and in the interests of reducing carbon emissions in accordance with Local Plan Policies LP19 and LP20 and London Plan Policies SI 1, SI 2 and SI 3.


21.	(Green Roof Plan): Notwithstanding the details under condition 2 of this permission, and prior to the first occupation/use of the development hereby permitted, details of the proposed green roofs, including their type, location and specific purpose together with maintenance schedule shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority. 

The green roof shall be constructed in accordance with the approved details and thereafter maintained in accordance with the approved maintenance schedule.

Reason: In order to reduce the impact of the development on the mains drainage system, enhance the insulation of the building, and contributing to biodiversity, improved air quality and amenity of the area in accordance with Policies LP21, LP26 and LP39 of the Council's Local Plan.


22.	(BREEAM): The development hereby permitted shall be constructed to achieve not less than BREEAM 'Excellent' or the equivalent standard in such measure of sustainability for non-residential building design which may replace that scheme. Within 12 months of the first occupation/use of the development, the final post construction BREEAM certificates(s) confirming that a BREEAM 'Excellent' rating has been achieved shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.

Reason: In the interest of sustainability, energy efficiency and to provide a high-quality development in accordance with the aims of Policy LP32 of the Local Plan.


23.	(Noise Management Plan): Notwithstanding the details submitted with the proposal hereby approved, prior to commencement of the superstructure works (excluding site clearance, demolition and preparatory construction works), a noise management plan (NMP) shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The Plan shall include but not limited to:
a)	Location and type of noise generating activities (indoor and outdoor areas) and proposed mitigation measures.
b)	Proposed monitoring (on and off site) to check compliance with noise limits
c)	How local residents and Council will be informed about an event.
d)	How noise complaint will be dealt with.
e)	Control on the operating hours for swimming classes or group activities located in open air spaces.
f)	Stipulate that Perth Road carpark shall be closed immediately after the facility closing time and shall remain closed until the following day whence open again.
 
The use hereby permitted shall thereafter be operated in accordance with the approved noise management plan. 
 
Reason: To protect the amenity for people living nearby, in accordance with Local Plan Policy LP24 and London Plan policies D13 and D14.


24.	(Controlling Plant Noise Emissions): Noise emitted from any new fixed building services plant and equipment shall be designed to a level at least 5 dB below the representative existing background sound level when assessed in accordance with BS 4142: 2014 + A1: 2019 at a position 1 m from the window (or a calculation thereof) to the nearest noise sensitive premises (i.e. Plant LAr,T = -5 dB LA90,T) by a Suitably Qualified Acoustician. This criterion applies to the total contribution of noise from all new plant items associated with the Proposed Development that may run during any particular period. The commissioning protocol shall be agreed in writing with the Local Planning Authority in advance of testing and the results shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to occupation of the relevant part of the scheme being tested and occupied. 

Reason: To ensure that there is no noise disturbance to neighbours in compliance with Local Plan Policy LP24 and London Plan policies D13 and D14.


COMPLIANCE CONDITIONS

25.	(Hours of use for external areas for a trial period of 18 months): External areas shall not be used outside the following times:

Recreational Areas (Splashpad and outdoor café) but excludes the swimming Pool:

Winter Months (September to February):     
  
Mon to Sat                                                  8.00 am - 8.00 pm 
Sunday, Public & Bank Holidays          10.00 am - 6.00 pm 

Summer Months (March to August):

Mon to Sat                                                  6.30 am - 9.00 pm 
Sunday, Public & Bank Holidays          9.00 am - 9.00 pm 

Swimming Pool, excluding the recreational Areas (Splashpad and outdoor café):

Winter Months (September to February):     

Mon to Sat                                                  6.30 am - 9.00 pm 
Sunday, Public & Bank Holidays          9.00 am - 9.00 pm 

Summer Months (March to August):

Mon to Sat                                                  6.30 am - 9.00 pm 
Sunday, Public & Bank Holidays          9.00 am - 9.00 pm 

Reason: In order to prevent the use causing an undue noise and disturbance to people living nearby at unreasonable hours of the day, and to accord with Local Plan Policy LP24 and London Plan policies D13 and D14.


26.	(Hours of use for external areas after 18 months trial period): Notwithstanding the hours of use approved under the condition 25, after 18 months from the commencement of the use, the external areas shall not be used outside of the times set out below until a written assessment of the impact on the residential amenity of neighbours has been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority.

Recreational Areas (Splashpad and outdoor café) but excludes the swimming Pool:

Winter Months (September to February):     
  
Mon to Sat                                                  8.00 am - 8.00 pm 
Sunday, Public & Bank Holidays          10.00 am - 6.00 pm 

Summer Months (March to August):

Mon to Sat                                                  6.30 am - 9.00 pm 
Sunday, Public & Bank Holidays          10.00 am - 7.00 pm 

Swimming Pool but exclude the recreational Areas (Splashpad and outdoor café):

Winter Months (September to February):     

Mon to Sat                                                  6.30 am - 9.00 pm 
Sunday, Public & Bank Holidays          10.00 am - 6.00 pm 

Summer Months (March to August):

Mon to Sat                                                  6.30 am - 9.00 pm 
Sunday, Public & Bank Holidays          10.00 am - 7.00 pm 

Reason: In order to prevent the use causing an undue noise and disturbance to people living nearby at unreasonable hours of the day, and to accord with Local Plan Policy LP24 and London Plan policies D13 and D14.


27.	(Amplified or other music- Outdoor): No amplified or other music shall be played in any external areas. 

Reason: To protect the amenity for people living nearby, in accordance with Local Plan Policy LP24 and London Plan policies D13 and D14.

28.	(Windows and Doors to be kept Close): All doors and windows to the premises shall be kept closed at all times except for the explicit purpose of entry to or exit from the premises.

Reason: To avoid unnecessary noise from open doors and windows, to protect the amenity for people living nearby in accordance with Local Plan Policy LP24 and London Plan policies D13 and D14.


29.	(Boilers):  Any non-CHP gas fired boilers installed in this development must achieve dry NOx emission levels no greater than 40 mg/kWh. 

Reason: To protect air quality and health in accordance with the aims of the 	Redbridge Local Plan and Air Quality Action Plan and Local Plan Policy LP24.


30.	(Water efficiency): The development hereby approved shall be designed to achieve at least the BREEAM excellent standard for the 'Wat 01' water category or equivalent.

Reason: To comply with London Plan Policy SI 5.


31.	(Cycle Parking): The development hereby approved shall provide 40 secure cycle spaces prior to the first occupation/use of the development. The approved cycle parking spaces shall thereafter be made permanently available and maintained for the relevant users of the development in accordance with the approved plans and details.

Reason: To ensure adequate cycle parking is available on site and to promote sustainable transport by reducing the need for car travel and ensure compliance with Policy LP23 of the Local Plan and  Policy T5 of the London Plan.
